w\">\u201cSilas Deane, Forgotten Patriot,\u201d<\/a> Journal of the American Revolution (Allthingsliberty.com), July 30, 2014, ; and Louis W. Potts, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.anb.org\/articles\/01\/01-00213.html?a=1&amp;n=silas%20deane&amp;d=10&amp;ss=0&amp;q=1\" rel=\"nofollow\">\u201cSilas Deane,\u201d<\/a> American National Biography.<\/p>\n\n<h2>About the Early American Manuscripts Project<\/h2>\n\n<p>With support from the The Polonsky Foundation, The New York Public Library is currently digitizing upwards of 50,000 pages of historic early American manuscript material. The Early American Manuscripts Project will allow students, researchers, and the general public to revisit major political events of the era from new perspectives and to explore currents of everyday social, cultural, and economic life in the colonial, revolutionary, and early national periods. The project will present on-line for the first time high quality facsimiles of key documents from America\u2019s Founding, including the papers of George Washington, Thomas Jefferson, Alexander Hamilton and James Madison. Drawing on the full breadth of the Library\u2019s\u00a0<a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/locations\/divisions\/manuscripts-division\">manuscript collections<\/a>, it will also make widely available less well-known manuscript sources, including business papers of Atlantic merchants, diaries of people ranging from elite New York women to Christian Indian preachers, and organizational records of voluntary associations and philanthropic organizations. Over the next two years, this trove of manuscript sources, previously available only at the Library, will be made freely available through nypl.org.<\/p>\n","safe_summary":"Political elites are well represented in archival collections. One of the great virtues for historians is that a lot of their family correspondence survives, though it is not always included in edited volumes that focus on political events. Through these papers we can glimpse family life at an emotional level."}]},"field_related_divisions":{"und":[{"nid":"5216"}]},"field_exhibitions":[],"field_program":[],"field_blog_channel":{"und":[{"nid":"106966"}]},"field_related_av":[],"field_related_pages":[],"field_nypl_person":[],"field_locations_libraries":{"und":[{"tid":"36"}]},"field_subject_taxonomy":{"und":[{"tid":"7870"},{"tid":"779"}]},"field_related_pubs":[],"field_audience_taxonomy":{"und":[{"tid":"915"},{"tid":"909"},{"tid":"774"},{"tid":"922"},{"tid":"738"},{"tid":"2793"},{"tid":"736"},{"tid":"739"},{"tid":"737"}]},"field_audience_supporters":[],"field_image_gallery_include":[],"field_blog_gallery_position":[],"field_blog_av_content_include":[],"field_blog_av_content_position":[],"field_file":[],"metatags":[],"cid":"0","last_comment_timestamp":"1450710469","last_comment_name":null,"last_comment_uid":"2461","comment_count":"0","name":"MarkBoonshoft@nypl.org","picture":"0","data":"b:0;","av_content":{"position":"bottom"},"_enhanced":{"summary_calculated":"Political elites are well represented in archival collections. One of the great virtues for historians is that a lot of their family correspondence survives, though it is not always included in edited volumes that focus on political events. Through these papers we can glimpse family life at an emotional level.","uri_relative":"\/blog\/2015\/12\/21\/silas-deane-reading-parenting-america","uri_absolute":"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/blog\/2015\/12\/21\/silas-deane-reading-parenting-america","user":{"uid":"2461","name":"MarkBoonshoft@nypl.org","pass":"$S$DG\/3.iBserOmG9W3gqqJhN5FG4BU4lRmbmoeWaPeAfA0huOmptIr","mail":"MarkBoonshoft@nypl.org","theme":"","signature":"","signature_format":"4","created":"1434131567","access":"1450963582","login":"1450710385","status":"1","timezone":"America\/New_York","language":"en","picture":null,"init":"MarkBoonshoft@nypl.org","data":false,"uuid":"6a7f5faf-4546-44b8-a5ba-da141722cd05","roles":{"2":"authenticated user","6":"staff","17":"blog writer"},"field_blog_title":[],"field_division_unit":{"und":[{"value":"Manuscripts and Archives Division","format":null,"safe_value":"Manuscripts and Archives Division"}]},"field_first_name":{"und":[{"value":"Mark","format":null,"safe_value":"Mark"}]},"field_last_name":{"und":[{"value":"Boonshoft","format":null,"safe_value":"Boonshoft"}]},"field_personal_bio":[],"field_site_contact":{"und":[{"value":"0"}]},"field_title_position":{"und":[{"value":"Post-Doctoral Research Fellow","format":null,"safe_value":"Post-Doctoral Research Fellow"}]},"field_user_location":[],"metatags":{"und":{"robots":{"value":{"0":0,"index":0,"follow":0,"noindex":0,"nofollow":0,"noarchive":0,"nosnippet":0,"noodp":0,"noydir":0}}}},"profile_author_name":"Mark Boonshoft","profile_bio":"","profile_blog_title":"","profile_feedburner_url":"","comment_notify_settings":{"uid":"2461","node_notify":"0","comment_notify":"1"}},"extracted_image":"http:\/\/images.nypl.org\/index.php?id=5248474&t=w"}},{"vid":"740771","uid":"2174","title":"The Library's New Mellon Director","log":"","status":"1","comment":"2","promote":"0","sticky":"0","vuuid":"71547a53-ae80-442b-9de4-f551fa500efe","nid":"328416","type":"blog","language":"en","created":"1450133653","changed":"1450134504","tnid":"0","translate":"0","uuid":"2a82597a-5124-451b-bc08-f510b4cfad13","revision_timestamp":"1450134504","revision_uid":"2551","body":{"und":[{"value":"<p style=\"text-align:center\">[[{\"fid\":\"293297\",\"view_mode\":\"default\",\"fields\":{\"format\":\"default\",\"field_file_image_alt_text[und][0][value]\":\"Bill Kelly\",\"field_file_image_title_text[und][0][value]\":\"Bill Kelly\"},\"type\":\"media\",\"attributes\":{\"alt\":\"Bill Kelly\",\"title\":\"Bill Kelly\",\"height\":\"333\",\"width\":\"500\",\"class\":\"media-element file-default\"}}]]<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>Today we share the news of the appointment of The New York Public Library&rsquo;s Andrew W. Mellon Director of the Research Libraries&mdash;William P. Kelly.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Library&#39;s Mellon Director leads the Library&#39;s four research centers and their 460 staff members&mdash;the Stephen A. Schwarzman Building on Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street; the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture; the Science, Industry and Business Library; and the Library for the Performing Arts at Lincoln Center. As Mellon Director, Bill will be charged with preserving and expanding the use of the most democratically accessible of research collections, which includes approximately 45 million items and is growing by about 150,000 books per year. He will begin his tenure in January.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bill is both an accomplished scholar and a true leader. Most recently, he was the interim chancellor of the City University of New York, after serving from 2005 to 2013 as president of the CUNY Graduate Center. He is also currently chairman of the John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation. At the CUNY Graduate Center, Bill has a well-earned reputation as an advocate for scholarly work, an institution builder, and a teacher and mentor. &nbsp;<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>Given his wealth of experience from these and many additional roles he has undertaken in his career, Bill has much to contribute to The New York Public Library. He arrives to a very full plate of activity, including: recruiting a number of new curators and staff; completing the second story of underground storage underneath Bryant Park so that we can again have as many or more books as ever on site&mdash;and now well preserved; working to ensure a great outcome from the Schwarzman Building renovation, which will open up approximately 40 percent more of the building to researchers and the general public; overseeing a $20 million renovation of the Schomburg Center; and much more. For more details, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/press\/press-release\/december-14-2015\/william-p-kelly-named-new-york-public-library%E2%80%99s-andrew-w-mellon\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"the news release about Bill's appointment\">please see the news release about Bill&#39;s appointment<\/a>.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are interested in joining our e-newsletter for researchers and scholars, <a href=\"http:\/\/pages.email.nypl.org\/researchmatters\">sign up here<\/a>.<\/p>\r\n","summary":"The Library's Mellon Director leads the Library's four research centers and their 460 staff members\u2014the Stephen A. Schwarzman Building on Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street; the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture; the Science, Industry and Business Library; and the Library for the Performing Arts at Lincoln Center. ","format":"4","safe_value":"<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"Bill Kelly\" title=\"Bill Kelly\" height=\"333\" width=\"500\" class=\"media-element file-default\" src=\"http:\/\/cdn-prod.www.aws.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Kelly600.png\" \/><\/p>\n\n<p>Today we share the news of the appointment of The New York Public Library\u2019s Andrew W. Mellon Director of the Research Libraries\u2014William P. Kelly.<\/p>\n\n<p>The Library's Mellon Director leads the Library's four research centers and their 460 staff members\u2014the Stephen A. Schwarzman Building on Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street; the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture; the Science, Industry and Business Library; and the Library for the Performing Arts at Lincoln Center. As Mellon Director, Bill will be charged with preserving and expanding the use of the most democratically accessible of research collections, which includes approximately 45 million items and is growing by about 150,000 books per year. He will begin his tenure in January.<\/p>\n\n<p>Bill is both an accomplished scholar and a true leader. Most recently, he was the interim chancellor of the City University of New York, after serving from 2005 to 2013 as president of the CUNY Graduate Center. He is also currently chairman of the John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation. At the CUNY Graduate Center, Bill has a well-earned reputation as an advocate for scholarly work, an institution builder, and a teacher and mentor. \u00a0<\/p>\n\n<p>Given his wealth of experience from these and many additional roles he has undertaken in his career, Bill has much to contribute to The New York Public Library. He arrives to a very full plate of activity, including: recruiting a number of new curators and staff; completing the second story of underground storage underneath Bryant Park so that we can again have as many or more books as ever on site\u2014and now well preserved; working to ensure a great outcome from the Schwarzman Building renovation, which will open up approximately 40 percent more of the building to researchers and the general public; overseeing a $20 million renovation of the Schomburg Center; and much more. For more details, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/press\/press-release\/december-14-2015\/william-p-kelly-named-new-york-public-library%E2%80%99s-andrew-w-mellon\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"the news release about Bill&#039;s appointment\">please see the news release about Bill's appointment<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you are interested in joining our e-newsletter for researchers and scholars, <a href=\"http:\/\/pages.email.nypl.org\/researchmatters\">sign up here<\/a>.<\/p>\n","safe_summary":"The Library's Mellon Director leads the Library's four research centers and their 460 staff members\u2014the Stephen A. Schwarzman Building on Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street; the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture; the Science, Industry and Business Library; and the Library for the Performing Arts at Lincoln Center. "}]},"field_related_divisions":[],"field_exhibitions":[],"field_program":[],"field_blog_channel":[],"field_related_av":[],"field_related_pages":[],"field_nypl_person":[],"field_locations_libraries":{"und":[{"tid":"55"},{"tid":"64"},{"tid":"65"},{"tid":"36"}]},"field_subject_taxonomy":{"und":[{"tid":"513"}]},"field_related_pubs":[],"field_audience_taxonomy":[],"field_audience_supporters":[],"field_image_gallery_include":[],"field_blog_gallery_position":[],"field_blog_av_content_include":[],"field_blog_av_content_position":[],"field_file":[],"metatags":[],"cid":"22059","last_comment_timestamp":"1450399508","last_comment_name":"ed","last_comment_uid":"0","comment_count":"1","name":"carolynbroomhead@nypl.org","picture":"0","data":"b:0;","av_content":{"position":"bottom"},"_enhanced":{"summary_calculated":"The Library's Mellon Director leads the Library's four research centers and their 460 staff members\u2014the Stephen A. Schwarzman Building on Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street; the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture; the Science, Industry and Business Library; and the Library for the Performing Arts at Lincoln Center. ","uri_relative":"\/blog\/2015\/12\/14\/new-mellon-director","uri_absolute":"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/blog\/2015\/12\/14\/new-mellon-director","user":{"uid":"2174","name":"carolynbroomhead@nypl.org","pass":"$S$DLmnOIKB8mO1GosEb1sMca8Tg6h4U\/4QA6rgGnL6N\/VYTk3SbOOa","mail":"carolynbroomhead@nypl.org","theme":"","signature":"","signature_format":"4","created":"1401298815","access":"1450123317","login":"1450111431","status":"1","timezone":"America\/New_York","language":"en","picture":null,"init":"carolynbroomhead@nypl.org","data":false,"uuid":"ba860ded-f04f-49f1-87b9-3a74f33750f4","roles":{"2":"authenticated user","6":"staff","16":"content editor","17":"blog writer"},"field_blog_title":[],"field_division_unit":[],"field_first_name":{"und":[{"value":"Carolyn","format":null,"safe_value":"Carolyn"}]},"field_last_name":{"und":[{"value":"Broomhead","format":null,"safe_value":"Broomhead"}]},"field_personal_bio":[],"field_site_contact":{"und":[{"value":"0"}]},"field_title_position":[],"field_user_location":[],"metatags":{"und":{"robots":{"value":{"0":0,"index":0,"follow":0,"noindex":0,"nofollow":0,"noarchive":0,"nosnippet":0,"noodp":0,"noydir":0}}}},"person":{"person_id":"62","first_name":"Carolyn","last_name":"Broomhead","account":"2174","uid":"0","created":"1434513317","changed":"1434513317","status":"1","module":null,"field_person_contact":{"und":[{"value":"0"}]},"field_person_division":[],"field_person_email":{"und":[{"email":""}]},"field_person_headshot":[],"field_person_links":[],"field_person_nypl_location":[],"field_person_phone":[],"field_person_position":[],"field_person_unit":[],"field_person_use_profile":{"und":[{"value":"0"}]},"field_profile_blog_biography":[],"field_profile_subject_biography":[],"field_profile_subject_expertise":[]},"profile_author_name":"Carolyn Broomhead","comment_notify_settings":{"uid":"2174","node_notify":"1","comment_notify":"1"}},"extracted_image":"http:\/\/cdn-prod.www.aws.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Kelly600.png"}},{"vid":"741663","uid":"1084","title":"Printing Women: Valerie Hammond","log":"","status":"1","comment":"2","promote":"0","sticky":"0","vuuid":"bef387bb-72ec-4a62-b19c-d6e229ee4c9c","nid":"328315","type":"blog","language":"en","created":"1450120278","changed":"1450299336","tnid":"0","translate":"0","uuid":"11441ec1-8dc3-459f-8e88-8559949376b5","revision_timestamp":"1450299336","revision_uid":"2399","body":{"und":[{"value":"<div class=\"digcol-image align-center\">\r\n\t<figure class=\"caption digcol-image\"><a data-url=\"b7cdda40-21cd-0133-6d40-58d385a7b928\" href=\"http:\/\/digitalcollections.nypl.org\/items\/b7cdda40-21cd-0133-6d40-58d385a7b928\"><img alt=\"Blue Anemone, Valerie Hammond\" data-id=\"5337711\" src=\"http:\/\/images.nypl.org\/index.php?id=5337711&amp;t=w\" width=\"300px\"><\/a>\r\n\r\n\t\t<figcaption class=\"digcol-caption\">Blue Anemone, Valerie Hammond, Lithograph, 2011<\/figcaption>\r\n\t<\/figure>\r\n<\/div>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>While the exhibition&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/events\/exhibitions\/printing-women\">Printing Women<\/a>&nbsp;focuses on Henrietta Louisa Koenen&rsquo;s (1830&ndash;1881) collection of female printmakers from the 16th to 19th centuries, it is only appropriate to signal women&rsquo;s continuing participation in the medium as well as the Library&rsquo;s longstanding commitment to acquiring and exhibiting prints made by women from around the world. To complement this earlier history, therefore, I worked with the Library&rsquo;s Digital Experience Team to display online&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/digitalcollections.nypl.org\/search\/index?filters[identifier]=DE%2015.12*#\">a small sampling of works by contemporary printmakers<\/a>&nbsp;in the Library&rsquo;s collection. We began reaching out to artists, asking if we could display their work on the exhibition&rsquo;s web page and digitize it for our&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/digitalcollections.nypl.org\/\">digital collections<\/a>. The majority were delighted to contribute, many also provided writings about their work and the exhibition. Throughout the exhibition&rsquo;s run, I will choose and present a piece by one artist every other week on the exhibition&rsquo;s web page. Additionally, I will produce a blog post about their work as well as about works in the exhibition, featuring their own words when possible.&nbsp;<\/em><\/p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>For those who are interested in the long history of women&rsquo;s involvement with the medium of print, there is much more to explore within the Library&rsquo;s deep and varied holdings. The exhibition features only&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/digitalcollections.nypl.org\/search\/index?filters[identifier]=TL%2015.12*#\">a smattering of Koenen&rsquo;s collection<\/a>&nbsp;(which numbers over 500 prints of which only a little over 80 are shown in the exhibition). In addition, the Print Collection not only owns large numbers of additional prints from the period in which Koenen collected, but also many, many more works from the 20th- and 21st-century.<\/em><\/p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>The fifth blog post in our series&nbsp;is by <a href=\"http:\/\/valeriehammond.com\">Valerie Hammond<\/a> about her piece, Blue Anemone, 2011.<\/em><\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Blue Anemone, made in 2011, was the result of a special collaboration with printmaker <a href=\"http:\/\/www.wildwoodpress.us\/#!artists\/c1c35\">Maryanne Simmons<\/a> of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.wildwoodpress.us\">Wildwood Press,<\/a> but the image&rsquo;s origins stemmed from a group of works I began a decade before.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>I started making <a href=\"http:\/\/www.littlejohncontemporary.com\/Hammond\/hammond_encaustic_03.php#.Vm9Mb3g0O-I\">tracings of hands<\/a> in the late 1990s, partly in response to the death of a dear friend from AIDS, whose beautiful hands I often found myself remembering. Mostly traced from women and children, each of the hand images was unique, an attempt at capturing the essence of a gesture and the fleeting moment in which it was made. Around the same time, in 1998, I was invited to teach printmaking at <a href=\"http:\/\/art.yale.edu\/Norfolk\">Yale University&rsquo;s Norfolk summer program<\/a>. Like many of the women in the exhibition I worked within the confines of children and family. My then&shy; young children came with me, and we spent time in the nearby woods, making fairy houses out of moss and ferns. I collected and pressed various fern fronds, attracted to their spindly forms and primordial origins.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>I soon began assembling the ferns inside the traced hands, securing them with layers of wax, their stems and fronds echoing the body&rsquo;s bones, veins and circulatory systems. Ferns, and then other plants, became both the material and &ldquo;tools&rdquo; for drawing, subverting traditional mark&shy;making methodologies. Later, I introduced printmaking, drawing and photographic techniques, like the Xerox transfer process, to the compositions, in order to further manipulate and &ldquo;distance&rdquo; the imagery. One night, experimenting in Photoshop, I accidentally inverted some of the images: the background darkened into a deep blue and the plant material turned ghostly white. The works suddenly inhabited a space I had been searching for, straddling the indefinable boundary between presence and absence, material and immaterial, consciousness and the unconscious. For me, they became emblematic not only of those whose hands I had traced, but of my own evolving artistic process &ndash; testimony to passing time and the quiet dissolution of memory.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"caption\" style=\"float:right\">[[{\"fid\":\"293290\",\"view_mode\":\"default\",\"fields\":{\"format\":\"default\",\"field_file_image_alt_text[und][0][value]\":\"Blue Anemone Flower\",\"field_file_image_title_text[und][0][value]\":\"Blue Anemone Flower\"},\"type\":\"media\",\"attributes\":{\"alt\":\"Blue Anemone Flower\",\"title\":\"Blue Anemone Flower\",\"height\":\"200\",\"width\":\"200\",\"class\":\"media-element file-default\"}}]]\r\n\t<figcaption>Blue Anemone, Photo by David Wright, 2011<\/figcaption>\r\n<\/figure>\r\n\r\n<p>Simmons first invited me to make prints at her St. Louis studio in 2006. Her huge presses enabled me to work at an unprecedented scale, with unprecedented freedom, and I developed a series of large, relief&shy; printed lithographs from my hand tracings. While I was working at Wildwood Press, a close friend of Maryanne&rsquo;s, Courtney, who at the time wore a bright pink wig, impressed me by her warmth and instant understanding of my process. My experience at Wildwood was rich and very meaningful; it was a collaborative environment among like&shy;minded women. Years later Maryanne told me that Courtney was terminally ill. Before Courtney died, Maryanne asked her son to trace her hands, knowing that Courtney would understand why. Maryanne then sent the tracings to me and asked me to begin a piece using her hands. As I set out looking for materials I came across some ethereal blue anemones in the garden. It turned out they were Courtney&rsquo;s favorite flower. She passed away before the print, Blue Anemone, was finished.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"digcol-image align-right inline\">\r\n\t<figure class=\"caption digcol-image\"><a data-url=\"510d47d9-4a5b-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99\" href=\"http:\/\/digitalcollections.nypl.org\/items\/510d47d9-4a5b-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99\"><img alt=\"Pilota sericea, Anna Atkins\" data-id=\"419523\" src=\"http:\/\/images.nypl.org\/index.php?id=419523&amp;t=w\" width=\"200px\"><\/a>\r\n\r\n\t\t<figcaption class=\"digcol-caption\">Pilota sericea, Anna Atkins, Cyanotype Impression, c.1850<\/figcaption>\r\n\t<\/figure>\r\n<\/div>\r\n\r\n<p>Women artists and printmakers have long been a huge influence on me. Obvious associations can be seen in Victorian botany photographs, like those of <a href=\"http:\/\/exhibitions.nypl.org\/treasures\/items\/show\/49\">Anna Atkins<\/a>, and the prints and watercolors of <a href=\"http:\/\/nmwa.org\/works\/plate-1-dissertation-insect-generations-and-metamorphosis-surinam\">Maria Sybilla Merian<\/a>. More immediately, I am indebted to the fearlessness of <a href=\"https:\/\/www.moma.org\/explore\/collection\/lb\/\">Louise Bourgeois<\/a>, the political feminism of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.art21.org\/artists\/nancy-spero\">Nancy Spero<\/a>, and the close friendship and collaboration I have with <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pbs.org\/art21\/artists\/kiki-smith\">Kiki Smith<\/a>, where we have spent many hours teaching printmaking together as well as working in various print shops together joyfully scratching on copper. &quot;<\/p>\r\n","summary":"Please click the image to view Valerie Hammond's blog about 'Blue Anemone' and \"the indefinable boundary between presence and absence.\" The exhibition, 'Printing Women' focuses on Henrietta Louisa Koenen\u2019s (1830\u20131881) collection and signals women\u2019s continuing participation in printmaking as well as the Library\u2019s longstanding commitment to acquiring and exhibiting prints made by women from around the world. ","format":"4","safe_value":"<div class=\"digcol-image align-center align-center\">\n\t<figure class=\"caption caption caption digcol-image\"><a href=\"http:\/\/digitalcollections.nypl.