x?filters[identifier]=TL%2015.12*#\">a smattering of Koenen\u2019s collection<\/a>\u00a0(which numbers over 500 prints of which only a little over 80 are shown in the exhibition). In addition, the Print Collection not only owns large numbers of additional prints from the period in which Koenen collected, but also many, many more works from the 20th- and 21st-century.<\/em>\n\n<\/p><p><em>The fifth blog post in our series\u00a0is by <a href=\"http:\/\/valeriehammond.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">Valerie Hammond<\/a> about her piece, Blue Anemone, 2011.<\/em><\/p>\n\n<p>\"Blue Anemone, made in 2011, was the result of a special collaboration with printmaker <a href=\"http:\/\/www.wildwoodpress.us\/#!artists\/c1c35\" rel=\"nofollow\">Maryanne Simmons<\/a> of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.wildwoodpress.us\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wildwood Press,<\/a> but the image\u2019s origins stemmed from a group of works I began a decade before.<\/p>\n\n<p>I started making <a href=\"http:\/\/www.littlejohncontemporary.com\/Hammond\/hammond_encaustic_03.php#.Vm9Mb3g0O-I\" rel=\"nofollow\">tracings of hands<\/a> in the late 1990s, partly in response to the death of a dear friend from AIDS, whose beautiful hands I often found myself remembering. Mostly traced from women and children, each of the hand images was unique, an attempt at capturing the essence of a gesture and the fleeting moment in which it was made. Around the same time, in 1998, I was invited to teach printmaking at <a href=\"http:\/\/art.yale.edu\/Norfolk\" rel=\"nofollow\">Yale University\u2019s Norfolk summer program<\/a>. Like many of the women in the exhibition I worked within the confines of children and family. My then\u00ad young children came with me, and we spent time in the nearby woods, making fairy houses out of moss and ferns. I collected and pressed various fern fronds, attracted to their spindly forms and primordial origins.<\/p>\n\n<p>I soon began assembling the ferns inside the traced hands, securing them with layers of wax, their stems and fronds echoing the body\u2019s bones, veins and circulatory systems. Ferns, and then other plants, became both the material and \u201ctools\u201d for drawing, subverting traditional mark\u00admaking methodologies. Later, I introduced printmaking, drawing and photographic techniques, like the Xerox transfer process, to the compositions, in order to further manipulate and \u201cdistance\u201d the imagery. One night, experimenting in Photoshop, I accidentally inverted some of the images: the background darkened into a deep blue and the plant material turned ghostly white. The works suddenly inhabited a space I had been searching for, straddling the indefinable boundary between presence and absence, material and immaterial, consciousness and the unconscious. For me, they became emblematic not only of those whose hands I had traced, but of my own evolving artistic process \u2013 testimony to passing time and the quiet dissolution of memory.<\/p>\n\n<figure class=\"caption caption caption\" style=\"float:right\"><img alt=\"Blue Anemone Flower\" title=\"Blue Anemone Flower\" height=\"200\" width=\"200\" class=\"media-element file-default\" src=\"http:\/\/cdn-prod.www.aws.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/600px-Blue_Anemone_%28Anemone_apennina%29.jpg\" \/><figcaption>Blue Anemone, Photo by David Wright, 2011<\/figcaption><\/figure><p>Simmons first invited me to make prints at her St. Louis studio in 2006. Her huge presses enabled me to work at an unprecedented scale, with unprecedented freedom, and I developed a series of large, relief\u00ad printed lithographs from my hand tracings. While I was working at Wildwood Press, a close friend of Maryanne\u2019s, Courtney, who at the time wore a bright pink wig, impressed me by her warmth and instant understanding of my process. My experience at Wildwood was rich and very meaningful; it was a collaborative environment among like\u00adminded women. Years later Maryanne told me that Courtney was terminally ill. Before Courtney died, Maryanne asked her son to trace her hands, knowing that Courtney would understand why. Maryanne then sent the tracings to me and asked me to begin a piece using her hands. As I set out looking for materials I came across some ethereal blue anemones in the garden. It turned out they were Courtney\u2019s favorite flower. She passed away before the print, Blue Anemone, was finished.<\/p>\n\n<div class=\"digcol-image align-right align-right inline inline\">\n\t<figure class=\"caption caption caption digcol-image\"><a href=\"http:\/\/digitalcollections.nypl.org\/items\/510d47d9-4a5b-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99\"><img alt=\"Pilota sericea, Anna Atkins\" src=\"http:\/\/images.nypl.org\/index.php?id=419523&amp;t=w\" width=\"200px\" \/><\/a>\n\n\t\t<figcaption class=\"digcol-caption\">Pilota sericea, Anna Atkins, Cyanotype Impression, c.1850<\/figcaption><\/figure><\/div>\n\n<p>Women artists and printmakers have long been a huge influence on me. Obvious associations can be seen in Victorian botany photographs, like those of <a href=\"http:\/\/exhibitions.nypl.org\/treasures\/items\/show\/49\">Anna Atkins<\/a>, and the prints and watercolors of <a href=\"http:\/\/nmwa.org\/works\/plate-1-dissertation-insect-generations-and-metamorphosis-surinam\" rel=\"nofollow\">Maria Sybilla Merian<\/a>. More immediately, I am indebted to the fearlessness of <a href=\"https:\/\/www.moma.org\/explore\/collection\/lb\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Louise Bourgeois<\/a>, the political feminism of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.art21.org\/artists\/nancy-spero\" rel=\"nofollow\">Nancy Spero<\/a>, and the close friendship and collaboration I have with <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pbs.org\/art21\/artists\/kiki-smith\" rel=\"nofollow\">Kiki Smith<\/a>, where we have spent many hours teaching printmaking together as well as working in various print shops together joyfully scratching on copper. \"<\/p>\n","safe_summary":"Please click the image to view Valerie Hammond's blog about 'Blue Anemone' and \"the indefinable boundary between presence and absence.\" The exhibition, 'Printing Women' focuses on Henrietta Louisa Koenen\u2019s (1830\u20131881) collection and signals women\u2019s continuing participation in printmaking as well as the Library\u2019s longstanding commitment to acquiring and exhibiting prints made by women from around the world. "}]},"field_related_divisions":{"und":[{"nid":"5221"}]},"field_exhibitions":{"und":[{"nid":"316642"}]},"field_program":[],"field_blog_channel":[],"field_related_av":[],"field_related_pages":[],"field_nypl_person":[],"field_locations_libraries":{"und":[{"tid":"36"}]},"field_subject_taxonomy":{"und":[{"tid":"580"}]},"field_related_pubs":[],"field_audience_taxonomy":[],"field_audience_supporters":[],"field_image_gallery_include":[],"field_blog_gallery_position":[],"field_blog_av_content_include":[],"field_blog_av_content_position":[],"field_file":[],"metatags":[],"cid":"0","last_comment_timestamp":"1450120278","last_comment_name":null,"last_comment_uid":"2399","comment_count":"0","name":"madeleineviljoen@nypl.org","picture":"0","data":"a:1:{s:13:\"form_build_id\";s:37:\"form-ec495e133880bee6466941c5bc66b006\";}","av_content":{"position":"bottom"},"_enhanced":{"summary_calculated":"Please click the image to view Valerie Hammond's blog about 'Blue Anemone' and \"the indefinable boundary between presence and absence.\" The exhibition, 'Printing Women' focuses on Henrietta Louisa Koenen\u2019s (1830\u20131881) collection and signals women\u2019s continuing participation in printmaking as well as the Library\u2019s longstanding commitment to acquiring and exhibiting prints made by women from around the world. ","uri_relative":"\/blog\/2015\/12\/14\/printing-women-valerie-hammond","uri_absolute":"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/blog\/2015\/12\/14\/printing-women-valerie-hammond","user":{"uid":"1084","name":"madeleineviljoen@nypl.org","pass":"$S$DRxvyXkJ09xpjtgcpnxcPQe5.XKZmi7OsUINSh2cvFtZOXLLQNDP","mail":"madeleineviljoen@nypl.org","theme":"","signature":"","signature_format":"4","created":"1315855862","access":"1443814330","login":"1443808416","status":"1","timezone":"America\/New_York","language":"en","picture":null,"init":"madeleineviljoen@nypl.org","data":{"form_build_id":"form-ec495e133880bee6466941c5bc66b006"},"uuid":"12b6556a-c263-40e3-86b4-8eac8b9dc7dd","roles":{"2":"authenticated user","6":"staff","17":"blog writer"},"field_blog_title":[],"field_division_unit":{"und":[{"value":"Photographs and Prints Division","format":null,"safe_value":"Photographs and Prints Division"}]},"field_first_name":{"und":[{"value":"Madeleine","format":null,"safe_value":"Madeleine"}]},"field_last_name":{"und":[{"value":"Viljoen","format":null,"safe_value":"Viljoen"}]},"field_personal_bio":[],"field_site_contact":{"und":[{"value":"0"}]},"field_title_position":{"und":[{"value":"Curator of Prints","format":null,"safe_value":"Curator of Prints"}]},"field_user_location":{"und":[{"value":"36"}]},"metatags":{"und":{"robots":{"value":{"0":0,"index":0,"follow":0,"noindex":0,"nofollow":0,"noarchive":0,"nosnippet":0,"noodp":0,"noydir":0}}}},"profile_author_name":"Madeleine Viljoen","comment_notify_settings":{"uid":"1084","node_notify":"1","comment_notify":"1"}},"extracted_image":"http:\/\/images.nypl.org\/index.php?id=5337711&t=w"}},{"vid":"738634","uid":"2219","title":"Santa's New York Roots","log":"","status":"1","comment":"2","promote":"0","sticky":"0","vuuid":"44445169-47f3-418c-a281-75ab8be33344","nid":"327735","type":"blog","language":"en","created":"1449683066","changed":"1449683066","tnid":"0","translate":"0","uuid":"ffd05300-4f95-42be-80de-243644bde6a9","revision_timestamp":"1449683066","revision_uid":"6","body":{"und":[{"value":"<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"digcol-image align-center\">\r\n\t<figure class=\"caption digcol-image\"><a data-url=\"510d47e3-6f96-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99\" href=\"http:\/\/digitalcollections.nypl.org\/items\/510d47e3-6f96-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99\"><img alt=\"Santas catch the trolley to Bloomingdales'\" data-id=\"1587014\" src=\"http:\/\/images.nypl.org\/index.php?id=1587014&amp;t=w\" width=\"100%\"><\/a>\r\n\r\n\t\t<figcaption class=\"digcol-caption\">&quot;Santas catch the trolley to Bloomingdale&#39;s&quot; Image ID:&nbsp;1587014<\/figcaption>\r\n\t<\/figure>\r\n<\/div>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Today there&rsquo;s no question about the identity of the jolly red-suited, white-bearded, toy-carrying plump old man: It&rsquo;s Santa Claus, of course. Throughout the mid-19th century, however, the identity of this famous gift giver was only just&nbsp;developing.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"digcol-image align-right inline\">\r\n\t<figure class=\"caption digcol-image\"><a data-url=\"510d47e3-48e5-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99#\/?uuid=510d47e3-48e5-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99\" href=\"http:\/\/digitalcollections.nypl.org\/items\/510d47e3-48e5-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99#\/?uuid=510d47e3-48e5-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99\"><img alt=\"&quot;A Merry Christmas&quot; postcard\" data-id=\"1587056\" src=\"http:\/\/images.nypl.org\/index.php?id=1587056&amp;t=w\" width=\"235px\"><\/a>\r\n\r\n\t\t<figcaption class=\"digcol-caption\">&quot;A Merry Christmas&quot;Image ID:&nbsp;1587056<\/figcaption>\r\n\t<\/figure>\r\n<\/div>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/archive.org\/stream\/stnicholashis00mckn#page\/n7\/mode\/2up\">Saint Nicholas<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Belsnickel\">Belsnickel<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Father_Christmas\">Father Christmas<\/a>, the <a href=\"https:\/\/books.google.com\/books?id=hkw2bPlfTUQC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;dq=%22santa+claus:+the+last+of+the+wild+men%22&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=0ahUKEwjMvqHy9L3JAhWLNz4KHW_SBC0Q6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&amp;q=%22santa%20claus%3A%20the%20last%20of%20the%20wild%20men%22&amp;f=false\">Wild Man<\/a>. While all of these cultural figures are symbolic of the holiday season, none are quite the jovial character we know and love today.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>So how was the iconic image of Santa born?<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>Several New Yorkers inspired the personality, appearance, and traditions of this holiday favorite. Through cultural influences, writings, and illustrations, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Pintard\">John Pintard<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Washington_Irving\">Washington Irving<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Clement_Clarke_Moore\">Clement C. Moore<\/a>, and <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thomas_Nast\">Thomas Nast<\/a> all helped to establish a modern representation of Santa Claus.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Jolly Old St. Nick<\/h2>\r\n\r\n<p>A number of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.stnicholascenter.org\/pages\/traditional-stories\/\">legends<\/a> associate Saint Nicholas with gift giving, aiding young people, imposing honesty, and rescuing those in need. As the patron saint of children and one of the most revered saints during the Middle Ages, folklore depicts Saint Nicholas as a giver of small gifts to well-behaved children on the eve of his <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/St_Nicholas_Day\">feast day<\/a>, December 6.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>Portrayed as an elderly white-bearded man dressed in red bishop&rsquo;s regalia, complete with staff and miter, Saint Nicholas delivered presents to children throughout Austria, the Netherlands, Belgium, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, and parts of Germany as early as the tenth century. This saint, despite his judgmental demeanor, was highly regarded by many 19th century New Yorkers and helped spark the evolution of an American Christmas gift giver.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"caption\" style=\"float:right\"><img alt=\"St. Nicholas Broadside, distributed to the New-York Historical Society for its first celebration of the Festival of St. Nicholas on December 6th, 1810, New-York Historical Society Library\" class=\"media-element file-default\" data-file_info=\"%7B%22fid%22:%22292968%22,%22view_mode%22:%22default%22,%22fields%22:%7B%22format%22:%22default%22,%22field_file_image_alt_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22St.%20Nicholas%20Broadside,%20distributed%20to%20the%20New-York%20Historical%20Society%20for%20its%20first%20celebration%20of%20the%20Festival%20of%20St.%20Nicholas%20on%20December%206th,%201810,%20New-York%20Historical%20Society%20Library%22,%22field_file_image_title_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22St.%20Nicholas%20Broadside,%20distributed%20to%20the%20New-York%20Historical%20Society%20for%20its%20first%20celebration%20of%20the%20Festival%20of%20St.%20Nicholas%20on%20December%206th,%201810,%20New-York%20Historical%20Society%20Library%22%7D,%22type%22:%22media%22%7D\" height=\"332\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/St.%20Nicholas%20broadside.png\" title=\"St. Nicholas Broadside, distributed to the New-York Historical Society for its first celebration of the Festival of St. Nicholas on December 6th, 1810, New-York Historical Society Library\" width=\"220\">\r\n\t<figcaption>Broadside of St. Nicholas,&nbsp;distributed to New-York Historical Society members, 1810&nbsp;(New-York Historical Society Library)<\/figcaption>\r\n<\/figure>\r\n\r\n<h2>Saint Nicholas in New York<\/h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Following the American Revolution, interest in the Dutch colonial history of New York surged, and Saint Nicholas became a favorite anti-British symbol of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nyhistory.org\/\">New York Historical Society<\/a> founder, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Pintard\">John Pintard<\/a>.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pintard held a strong interest in Saint Nicholas, promoting him as the patron saint of both the Society and the city as a whole throughout the early 1800s. Annual Society meetings were held on Saint Nicholas&rsquo; feast day,&nbsp;members were issued Saint Nicholas promotional materials, and Pintard even staged (unintentionally terrifying) visits between Saint Nicholas and his family.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n\t<p>&ldquo;To the memory of St. Nicholas. May the virtuous habits and simple manners of our Dutch ancestors be not lost in the luxuries and refinements of the present time&rdquo; &mdash;<a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/David_Hosack\">Dr. David Hosack<\/a>, New York Historical Society Banquet, 1809<\/p>\r\n<\/blockquote>\r\n\r\n<h2>Knickerbocker&#39;s History<\/h2>\r\n\r\n<p>This local promotion of Saint Nicholas attracted the attention of New York writer, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Washington_Irving\">Washington Irving<\/a>.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Irving joined the New York Historical Society while writing the 1809 <a href=\"https:\/\/archive.org\/stream\/ldpd_11290370_000#page\/n9\/mode\/2up\">Knickerbocker&rsquo;s History of New York<\/a>. Likely <a href=\"http:\/\/www.stnicholascenter.org\/pages\/knickerbocker\/\">inspired by Pintard<\/a>, Irving featured Saint Nicholas prominently in this satirical history of the New Amsterdam Dutch, depicting him as a symbol of Dutch-American ethnic identity.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\r\n\t<figure class=\"caption\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"Knickerbocker&amp;#039;s History of New York, p. 136\" class=\"media-element file-default\" data-file_info=\"%7B%22fid%22:%22292969%22,%22view_mode%22:%22default%22,%22fields%22:%7B%22format%22:%22default%22,%22field_file_image_alt_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22Knickerbocker's%20History%20of%20New%20York,%20p.%20136%22,%22field_file_image_title_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22Knickerbocker's%20History%20of%20New%20York,%20p.%20136%22%7D,%22type%22:%22media%22%7D\" height=\"84\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Knickerbocker%20-%20Presents%20in%20chimneys.png\" title=\"Knickerbocker&amp;#039;s History of New York, p. 136\" width=\"375\">\r\n\t\t<figcaption>Knickerbocker&#39;s History of New York, p. 136<\/figcaption>\r\n\t<\/figure>\r\n<\/div>\r\n\r\n<p>Altering the saint&rsquo;s appearance from the tall, somber, commanding European image, Irving reinvented Saint Nicholas as a short, stout, merry, pipe-smoking Dutchman, dressed in traditional colonial attire. Though Irving sparked an initial transformation of Saint Nicholas, this Christmas figure was still far from the image of Santa Claus we know today.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\r\n\t<figure class=\"caption\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly, December 20, 1884, &amp;quot;Hello Little One,&amp;quot; by Thomas Nast\" class=\"media-element file-default\" data-file_info=\"%7B%22fid%22:%22292999%22,%22view_mode%22:%22default%22,%22fields%22:%7B%22format%22:%22default%22,%22field_file_image_alt_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22Harper's%20Weekly,%20December%2020,%201884,%20%5C%22Hello%20Little%20One,%5C%22%20by%20Thomas%20Nast%22,%22field_file_image_title_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22Harper's%20Weekly,%20December%2020,%201884,%20%5C%22Hello%20Little%20One,%5C%22%20by%20Thomas%20Nast%22%7D,%22type%22:%22media%22%7D\" height=\"408\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Nast%20-%20Hello%20Little%20one%2C%20dec%2020%201884.png\" title=\"Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly, December 20, 1884, &amp;quot;Hello Little One,&amp;quot; by Thomas Nast\" width=\"325\">\r\n\t\t<figcaption>&quot;Hello Little One!&quot; Thomas Nast, Harper&#39;s Weekly<\/figcaption>\r\n\t<\/figure>\r\n<\/div>\r\n\r\n<h2>&lsquo;Twas the Night Before Christmas<\/h2>\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"caption\" style=\"float:right\"><img alt=\"&amp;quot;For He&amp;#039;s a Jolly Good Fellow,&amp;quot; by Thomas Nast, Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly\" class=\"media-element file-default\" data-file_info=\"%7B%22fid%22:%22293004%22,%22view_mode%22:%22default%22,%22fields%22:%7B%22format%22:%22default%22,%22field_file_image_alt_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22%5C%22For%20He's%20a%20Jolly%20Good%20Fellow,%5C%22%20by%20Thomas%20Nast,%20Harper's%20Weekly%22,%22field_file_image_title_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22%5C%22For%20He's%20a%20Jolly%20Good%20Fellow,%5C%22%20by%20Thomas%20Nast,%20Harper's%20Weekly%22%7D,%22type%22:%22media%22%7D\" height=\"360\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/nast%20-%20for%20he%27s%20a%20jolly%20good%20fellow%2C%20so%20say%20we%20all%20of%20us.png\" title=\"&amp;quot;For He&amp;#039;s a Jolly Good Fellow,&amp;quot; by Thomas Nast, Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly\" width=\"300\">\r\n\t<figcaption>&quot;For he&#39;s a jolly good fellow!&quot; Thomas Nast, Harper&#39;s Weekly<\/figcaption>\r\n<\/figure>\r\n\r\n<p>It was not until the 1822 poem, &ldquo;<a href=\"https:\/\/archive.org\/stream\/visitfromstnicho00moor#page\/n7\/mode\/2up\">A Visit from Saint Nicholas<\/a>,&rdquo; when the familiar spirit of Santa Claus truly began to&nbsp;unfold. Written by <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Clement_Clarke_Moore\">Clement C. Moore<\/a>, a professor at New York&rsquo;s <a href=\"https:\/\/www.gts.edu\/\">General Theological Seminary<\/a>, this poem created an unprecedented characterization of Saint Nicholas.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>Recognizable by its opening line, &ldquo;&lsquo;Twas the night before Christmas,&rdquo; Moore tells a story of a plump &ldquo;jolly old elf&rdquo; who traveled by reindeer-pulled sleigh and descended down chimneys to deliver presents to children&rsquo;s stockings. A friend of Washington Irving, it is speculated that Moore&rsquo;s version of Saint Nicholas was inspired by descriptions in <a href=\"https:\/\/archive.org\/stream\/ldpd_11290370_000#page\/n9\/mode\/2up\">Knickerbocker&rsquo;s History of New York<\/a>, and by real-life&nbsp;characteristics of&nbsp;the <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Wouter_van_Twiller\">first governor of New Netherland<\/a>&nbsp;and a portly Dutch neighbor of Moore&rsquo;s.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many details now synonymous with the legend of Santa Claus were first introduced in this poem, including changing Saint Nicholas&rsquo; visit to Christmas Eve instead of the Saint&rsquo;s feast day or New Year&rsquo;s Eve. While there lies some controversy about whether Moore was <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Henry_Livingston,_Jr.\">the true author of this poem<\/a>, this depiction left a lasting imprint on American culture, forever changing Christmas lore.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\r\n\t<figure class=\"caption\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"New York American, January 3, 1824\" class=\"media-element file-default\" data-file_info=\"%7B%22fid%22:%22292975%22,%22view_mode%22:%22default%22,%22fields%22:%7B%22format%22:%22default%22,%22field_file_image_alt_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22New%20York%20American,%20January%203,%201824%22,%22field_file_image_title_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22New%20York%20American,%20January%203,%201824%22%7D,%22type%22:%22media%22%7D\" height=\"237\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/New%20York%20American%201-3-1824.png\" title=\"New York American, January 3, 1824\" width=\"305\">\r\n\t\t<figcaption>New York American, January 3, 1824<\/figcaption>\r\n\t<\/figure>\r\n<\/div>\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"caption\" style=\"float:right\"><img alt=\"An Ode to Saint Claas, January 4, 1828\" class=\"media-element file-default\" data-file_info=\"%7B%22fid%22:%22292973%22,%22view_mode%22:%22default%22,%22fields%22:%7B%22format%22:%22default%22,%22field_file_image_alt_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22An%20Ode%20to%20Saint%20Claas,%20January%204,%201828%22,%22field_file_image_title_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22An%20Ode%20to%20Saint%20Claas,%20January%204,%201828%22%7D,%22type%22:%22media%22%7D\" height=\"207\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Ode%20to%20St.%20Claas%20-%20New%20York%20American%20-%201-4-1828.png\" title=\"An Ode to Saint Claas, January 4, 1828\" width=\"250\">\r\n\t<figcaption>New York American, January 4, 1828<\/figcaption>\r\n<\/figure>\r\n\r\n<h2>Sinterklaas<\/h2>\r\n\r\n<p>As the Americanized version of Saint Nicholas gained distinction from his European predecessor, so did his name.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>Though Sinterklaas is the Dutch phrase for Saint Nicholas, this word posed some difficulty for American English speakers and prompted an evolution of the gift giver&rsquo;s title. Before Americans collectively settled on &ldquo;Santa Claus,&rdquo; some early naming attempts include St. Aclaus, St. Iclaus, Sancte Klaas, St. Claas, St. a claus, and Santeclaw.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<h2>A Signature Look<\/h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Interpretations of Santa&rsquo;s appearance were very imaginative throughout the 19th century. Depictions ranged from thin to fat, elf-like to human man, and costumes were not standardized; No one was quite sure what this gift-giver should look like.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"caption\" style=\"float:right\"><img alt=\"Depiction of Santa Claus, Dollar Newspaper, Philadelphia, PA, December 25, 1844\" class=\"media-element file-default\" data-file_info=\"%7B%22fid%22:%22293056%22,%22view_mode%22:%22default%22,%22fields%22:%7B%22format%22:%22default%22,%22field_file_image_alt_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22Depiction%20of%20Santa%20Claus,%20Dollar%20Newspaper,%20Philadelphia,%20PA,%20December%2025,%201844%22,%22field_file_image_title_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22Depiction%20of%20Santa%20Claus,%20Dollar%20Newspaper,%20Philadelphia,%20PA,%20December%2025,%201844%22%7D,%22type%22:%22media%22%7D\" height=\"282\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Dollar%20Newspaper%20-%20Philadelphia%20PA%20-%2012-25-1844%20%282%29.png\" title=\"Depiction of Santa Claus, Dollar Newspaper, Philadelphia, PA, December 25, 1844\" width=\"300\">\r\n\t<figcaption>Early depiction of Santa Claus<br>\r\n\t\tDollar Newspaper (Philadelphia, Pennsylvania)<br>\r\n\t\tDecember 25, 1844<\/figcaption>\r\n<\/figure>\r\n\r\n<p>It wasn&rsquo;t until the <a href=\"https:\/\/archive.org\/stream\/gri_33125008808467#page\/n7\/mode\/2up\">illustrations of Thomas Nast<\/a>, a German-born New Yorker and <em><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/collections\/articles-databases\/harpweek\">Harper&rsquo;s Weekly<\/a><\/em> cartoonist, that an enduring image of Santa Claus was established.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>Creating an entire world for Santa built upon the traditions described by Clement Moore and the influences of <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Belsnickel\">German Christmas folklore<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thomas_Nast\">Nast<\/a> captured trademark elements of Santa&rsquo;s image as his drawings evolved. A long white beard, black boots, and red suit trimmed with fur are just a few of these identifying features. Portrayed as a round, cheerful, elderly man, Nast&#39;s&nbsp;drawings also added some key details to Santa&rsquo;s backstory: a home at the North Pole and toy-building elf assistants.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>Santa&#39;s celebrity status and iconic appearance was further cemeted in&nbsp;roles such as&nbsp;Coca Cola&rsquo;s longstanding <a href=\"http:\/\/www.coca-cola.co.uk\/stories\/history\/advertising\/coca-cola-and-father-christmas-the-sundblom-santa-story\/\">advertising campaign<\/a>&nbsp;and growing holiday commercialism.&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\r\n\t<figure class=\"caption\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"Cover of Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly, December 30, 1871, &amp;quot;Letters from Naughty Children&amp;#039;s Parents&amp;quot;\" class=\"media-element file-default\" data-file_info=\"%7B%22fid%22:%22292981%22,%22view_mode%22:%22default%22,%22fields%22:%7B%22format%22:%22default%22,%22field_file_image_alt_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22Cover%20of%20Harper's%20Weekly,%20December%2030,%201871,%20%5C%22Letters%20from%20Naughty%20Children's%20Parents%5C%22%22,%22field_file_image_title_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22Cover%20of%20Harper's%20Weekly,%20December%2030,%201871,%20%5C%22Letters%20from%20Naughty%20Children's%20Parents%5C%22%22%7D,%22type%22:%22media%22%7D\" height=\"528\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Harper%27s%20weekly%20cover%20-%20dec%2030%201871%20-%20letters%20from%20naughty%20children%27s%20parents.jpg\" title=\"Cover of Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly, December 30, 1871, &amp;quot;Letters from Naughty Children&amp;#039;s Parents&amp;quot;\" width=\"375\">\r\n\t\t<figcaption>&quot;Letters from Naughty Children&#39;s Parents,&quot; Harper&#39;s Weekly, December 30, 1871<\/figcaption>\r\n\t<\/figure>\r\n<\/div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"line-height: 19.0909080505371px;\">A figure rooted in centuries-old legends and decades-long American transformation, Santa Claus as a pop culture icon is here to stay.<\/span><\/p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Further Reading<\/h2>\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"caption\" style=\"float:right\"><img alt=\"Santa is an All-American, Chicago Daily Tribune 12-18-1950\" class=\"media-element file-default\" data-file_info=\"%7B%22fid%22:%22292970%22,%22view_mode%22:%22default%22,%22fields%22:%7B%22format%22:%22default%22,%22field_file_image_alt_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22Santa%20is%20an%20All-American,%20Chicago%20Daily%20Tribune%2012-18-1950%22,%22field_file_image_title_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22Santa%20is%20an%20All-American,%20Chicago%20Daily%20Tribune%2012-18-1950%22%7D,%22type%22:%22media%22%7D\" height=\"156\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Chicago%20Daily%20Tribune%2012-18-1950.png\" title=\"Santa is an All-American, Chicago Daily Tribune 12-18-1950\" width=\"230\">\r\n\t<figcaption>Chicago Daily Tribune, December 18, 1950<\/figcaption>\r\n<\/figure>\r\n\r\n<p>Learn more about the history of Santa Claus&nbsp;through the following materials:<\/p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><em><a href=\"http:\/\/catalog.nypl.org\/record=b17783430~S1\">Christmas in America: A History<\/a><\/em><\/li>\r\n\t<li><em><a href=\"http:\/\/catalog.nypl.org\/record=b14961416~S1\">Encyclopedia of Christmas<\/a><\/em><\/li>\r\n\t<li><em><a href=\"http:\/\/catalog.nypl.org\/record=b16099065~S1\">Encyclopedia of New York State<\/a><\/em>: &ldquo;St. Nicholas&rdquo;<\/li>\r\n\t<li><em><a href=\"http:\/\/www.stnicholascenter.org\/pages\/knickerbocker\/\">Knickerbocker Santa Claus<\/a><\/em><\/li>\r\n\t<li><em><a href=\"http:\/\/catalog.nypl.org\/record=b12768319~S1\">Santa Claus, Last of the Wild Men<\/a><\/em><\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Find Thomas Nast&rsquo;s <em>Harper&rsquo;s Weekly<\/em> illustrations of Santa Claus in the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/collections\/articles-databases\/harpweek\">HarpWeek<\/a> database. Also search for articles describing early St. Nicholas and&nbsp;Santa Claus traditions in the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/collections\/articles-databases\/americas-historical-newspapers\">America&rsquo;s Historical Newspapers<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/collections\/articles-databases\/proquest-historical-database\">Proquest Historical Newspapers<\/a> databases.<\/p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\r\n\t<figure class=\"caption\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"First mention of &amp;quot;St. a Claus,&amp;quot; Rivington&amp;#039;s New-New Gazetteer, December 23, 1773\" class=\"media-element file-default\" data-file_info=\"%7B%22fid%22:%22292972%22,%22view_mode%22:%22default%22,%22fields%22:%7B%22format%22:%22default%22,%22field_file_image_alt_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22First%20mention%20of%20%5C%22St.%20a%20Claus,%5C%22%20Rivington's%20New-New%20Gazetteer,%20December%2023,%201773%22,%22field_file_image_title_text%5Bund%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D%22:%22First%20mention%20of%20%5C%22St.%20a%20Claus,%5C%22%20Rivington's%20New-New%20Gazetteer,%20December%2023,%201773%22%7D,%22type%22:%22media%22%7D\" height=\"63\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/1st%20mention%20of%20St.%20a%20Claus%20-%20Rivington%27s%20New-York%20Gazetteer.png\" title=\"First mention of &amp;quot;St. a Claus,&amp;quot; Rivington&amp;#039;s New-New Gazetteer, December 23, 1773\" width=\"340\">\r\n\t\t<figcaption>The first mention of a Santa Claus figure:&quot;St. a Claus,&quot; Rivington&#39;s New-York Gazetteer, December 23, 1773<\/figcaption>\r\n\t<\/figure>\r\n<\/div>\r\n","summary":"How was the iconic image of Santa born? Several New Yorkers inspired the personality, appearance, and traditions of this holiday favorite.","format":"4","safe_value":"<p>\u00a0<\/p>\n\n<div class=\"digcol-image align-center align-center\">\n\t<figure class=\"caption caption caption digcol-image\"><a href=\"http:\/\/digitalcollections.nypl.org\/items\/510d47e3-6f96-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99\"><img alt=\"Santas catch the trolley to Bloomingdales&#039;\" src=\"http:\/\/images.nypl.org\/index.php?id=1587014&amp;t=w\" width=\"100%\" \/><\/a>\n\n\t\t<figcaption class=\"digcol-caption\">\"Santas catch the trolley to Bloomingdale's\" Image ID:\u00a01587014<\/figcaption><\/figure><\/div>\n\n<p>Today there\u2019s no question about the identity of the jolly red-suited, white-bearded, toy-carrying plump old man: It\u2019s Santa Claus, of course. Throughout the mid-19th century, however, the identity of this famous gift giver was only just\u00a0developing.<\/p>\n\n<div class=\"digcol-image align-right align-right inline inline\">\n\t<figure class=\"caption caption caption digcol-image\"><a href=\"http:\/\/digitalcollections.nypl.org\/items\/510d47e3-48e5-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99#\/?uuid=510d47e3-48e5-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99\"><img alt=\"&quot;A Merry Christmas&quot; postcard\" src=\"http:\/\/images.nypl.org\/index.php?id=1587056&amp;t=w\" width=\"235px\" \/><\/a>\n\n\t\t<figcaption class=\"digcol-caption\">\"A Merry Christmas\"Image ID:\u00a01587056<\/figcaption><\/figure><\/div>\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/archive.org\/stream\/stnicholashis00mckn#page\/n7\/mode\/2up\" rel=\"nofollow\">Saint Nicholas<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Belsnickel\" rel=\"nofollow\">Belsnickel<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Father_Christmas\" rel=\"nofollow\">Father Christmas<\/a>, the <a href=\"https:\/\/books.google.com\/books?id=hkw2bPlfTUQC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;dq=%22santa+claus:+the+last+of+the+wild+men%22&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=0ahUKEwjMvqHy9L3JAhWLNz4KHW_SBC0Q6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&amp;q=%22santa%20claus%3A%20the%20last%20of%20the%20wild%20men%22&amp;f=false\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wild Man<\/a>. While all of these cultural figures are symbolic of the holiday season, none are quite the jovial character we know and love today.<\/p>\n\n<p>So how was the iconic image of Santa born?<\/p>\n\n<p>Several New Yorkers inspired the personality, appearance, and traditions of this holiday favorite. Through cultural influences, writings, and illustrations, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Pintard\" rel=\"nofollow\">John Pintard<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Washington_Irving\" rel=\"nofollow\">Washington Irving<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Clement_Clarke_Moore\" rel=\"nofollow\">Clement C. Moore<\/a>, and <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thomas_Nast\" rel=\"nofollow\">Thomas Nast<\/a> all helped to establish a modern representation of Santa Claus.<\/p>\n\n<h2>Jolly Old St. Nick<\/h2>\n\n<p>A number of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.stnicholascenter.org\/pages\/traditional-stories\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">legends<\/a> associate Saint Nicholas with gift giving, aiding young people, imposing honesty, and rescuing those in need. As the patron saint of children and one of the most revered saints during the Middle Ages, folklore depicts Saint Nicholas as a giver of small gifts to well-behaved children on the eve of his <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/St_Nicholas_Day\" rel=\"nofollow\">feast day<\/a>, December 6.<\/p>\n\n<p>Portrayed as an elderly white-bearded man dressed in red bishop\u2019s regalia, complete with staff and miter, Saint Nicholas delivered presents to children throughout Austria, the Netherlands, Belgium, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, and parts of Germany as early as the tenth century. This saint, despite his judgmental demeanor, was highly regarded by many 19th century New Yorkers and helped spark the evolution of an American Christmas gift giver.<\/p>\n\n<figure class=\"caption caption caption\" style=\"float:right\"><img alt=\"St. Nicholas Broadside, distributed to the New-York Historical Society for its first celebration of the Festival of St. Nicholas on December 6th, 1810, New-York Historical Society Library\" class=\"media-element file-default\" height=\"332\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/St.%20Nicholas%20broadside.png\" title=\"St. Nicholas Broadside, distributed to the New-York Historical Society for its first celebration of the Festival of St. Nicholas on December 6th, 1810, New-York Historical Society Library\" width=\"220\" \/><figcaption>Broadside of St. Nicholas,\u00a0distributed to New-York Historical Society members, 1810\u00a0(New-York Historical Society Library)<\/figcaption><\/figure><h2>Saint Nicholas in New York<\/h2>\n\n<p>Following the American Revolution, interest in the Dutch colonial history of New York surged, and Saint Nicholas became a favorite anti-British symbol of <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nyhistory.org\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">New York Historical Society<\/a> founder, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Pintard\" rel=\"nofollow\">John Pintard<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Pintard held a strong interest in Saint Nicholas, promoting him as the patron saint of both the Society and the city as a whole throughout the early 1800s. Annual Society meetings were held on Saint Nicholas\u2019 feast day,\u00a0members were issued Saint Nicholas promotional materials, and Pintard even staged (unintentionally terrifying) visits between Saint Nicholas and his family.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n\t<p>\u201cTo the memory of St. Nicholas. May the virtuous habits and simple manners of our Dutch ancestors be not lost in the luxuries and refinements of the present time\u201d \u2014<a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/David_Hosack\" rel=\"nofollow\">Dr. David Hosack<\/a>, New York Historical Society Banquet, 1809<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<h2>Knickerbocker's History<\/h2>\n\n<p>This local promotion of Saint Nicholas attracted the attention of New York writer, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Washington_Irving\" rel=\"nofollow\">Washington Irving<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Irving joined the New York Historical Society while writing the 1809 <a href=\"https:\/\/archive.org\/stream\/ldpd_11290370_000#page\/n9\/mode\/2up\" rel=\"nofollow\">Knickerbocker\u2019s History of New York<\/a>. Likely <a href=\"http:\/\/www.stnicholascenter.org\/pages\/knickerbocker\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">inspired by Pintard<\/a>, Irving featured Saint Nicholas prominently in this satirical history of the New Amsterdam Dutch, depicting him as a symbol of Dutch-American ethnic identity.<\/p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n\t<figure class=\"caption caption caption\"><img alt=\"Knickerbocker&amp;#039;s History of New York, p. 136\" class=\"media-element file-default\" height=\"84\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Knickerbocker%20-%20Presents%20in%20chimneys.png\" title=\"Knickerbocker&amp;#039;s History of New York, p. 136\" width=\"375\" \/><figcaption>Knickerbocker's History of New York, p. 136<\/figcaption><\/figure><\/div>\n\n<p>Altering the saint\u2019s appearance from the tall, somber, commanding European image, Irving reinvented Saint Nicholas as a short, stout, merry, pipe-smoking Dutchman, dressed in traditional colonial attire. Though Irving sparked an initial transformation of Saint Nicholas, this Christmas figure was still far from the image of Santa Claus we know today.<\/p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n\t<figure class=\"caption caption caption\"><img alt=\"Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly, December 20, 1884, &amp;quot;Hello Little One,&amp;quot; by Thomas Nast\" class=\"media-element file-default\" height=\"408\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Nast%20-%20Hello%20Little%20one%2C%20dec%2020%201884.png\" title=\"Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly, December 20, 1884, &amp;quot;Hello Little One,&amp;quot; by Thomas Nast\" width=\"325\" \/><figcaption>\"Hello Little One!\" Thomas Nast, Harper's Weekly<\/figcaption><\/figure><\/div>\n\n<h2>\u2018Twas the Night Before Christmas<\/h2>\n\n<figure class=\"caption caption caption\" style=\"float:right\"><img alt=\"&amp;quot;For He&amp;#039;s a Jolly Good Fellow,&amp;quot; by Thomas Nast, Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly\" class=\"media-element file-default\" height=\"360\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/nast%20-%20for%20he%27s%20a%20jolly%20good%20fellow%2C%20so%20say%20we%20all%20of%20us.png\" title=\"&amp;quot;For He&amp;#039;s a Jolly Good Fellow,&amp;quot; by Thomas Nast, Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly\" width=\"300\" \/><figcaption>\"For he's a jolly good fellow!\" Thomas Nast, Harper's Weekly<\/figcaption><\/figure><p>It was not until the 1822 poem, \u201c<a href=\"https:\/\/archive.org\/stream\/visitfromstnicho00moor#page\/n7\/mode\/2up\" rel=\"nofollow\">A Visit from Saint Nicholas<\/a>,\u201d when the familiar spirit of Santa Claus truly began to\u00a0unfold. Written by <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Clement_Clarke_Moore\" rel=\"nofollow\">Clement C. Moore<\/a>, a professor at New York\u2019s <a href=\"https:\/\/www.gts.edu\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">General Theological Seminary<\/a>, this poem created an unprecedented characterization of Saint Nicholas.<\/p>\n\n<p>Recognizable by its opening line, \u201c\u2018Twas the night before Christmas,\u201d Moore tells a story of a plump \u201cjolly old elf\u201d who traveled by reindeer-pulled sleigh and descended down chimneys to deliver presents to children\u2019s stockings. A friend of Washington Irving, it is speculated that Moore\u2019s version of Saint Nicholas was inspired by descriptions in <a href=\"https:\/\/archive.org\/stream\/ldpd_11290370_000#page\/n9\/mode\/2up\" rel=\"nofollow\">Knickerbocker\u2019s History of New York<\/a>, and by real-life\u00a0characteristics of\u00a0the <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Wouter_van_Twiller\" rel=\"nofollow\">first governor of New Netherland<\/a>\u00a0and a portly Dutch neighbor of Moore\u2019s.<\/p>\n\n<p>Many details now synonymous with the legend of Santa Claus were first introduced in this poem, including changing Saint Nicholas\u2019 visit to Christmas Eve instead of the Saint\u2019s feast day or New Year\u2019s Eve. While there lies some controversy about whether Moore was <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Henry_Livingston,_Jr.\" rel=\"nofollow\">the true author of this poem<\/a>, this depiction left a lasting imprint on American culture, forever changing Christmas lore.<\/p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n\t<figure class=\"caption caption caption\"><img alt=\"New York American, January 3, 1824\" class=\"media-element file-default\" height=\"237\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/New%20York%20American%201-3-1824.png\" title=\"New York American, January 3, 1824\" width=\"305\" \/><figcaption>New York American, January 3, 1824<\/figcaption><\/figure><\/div>\n\n<figure class=\"caption caption caption\" style=\"float:right\"><img alt=\"An Ode to Saint Claas, January 4, 1828\" class=\"media-element file-default\" height=\"207\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Ode%20to%20St.%20Claas%20-%20New%20York%20American%20-%201-4-1828.png\" title=\"An Ode to Saint Claas, January 4, 1828\" width=\"250\" \/><figcaption>New York American, January 4, 1828<\/figcaption><\/figure><h2>Sinterklaas<\/h2>\n\n<p>As the Americanized version of Saint Nicholas gained distinction from his European predecessor, so did his name.<\/p>\n\n<p>Though Sinterklaas is the Dutch phrase for Saint Nicholas, this word posed some difficulty for American English speakers and prompted an evolution of the gift giver\u2019s title. Before Americans collectively settled on \u201cSanta Claus,\u201d some early naming attempts include St. Aclaus, St. Iclaus, Sancte Klaas, St. Claas, St. a claus, and Santeclaw.<\/p>\n\n<h2>A Signature Look<\/h2>\n\n<p>Interpretations of Santa\u2019s appearance were very imaginative throughout the 19th century. Depictions ranged from thin to fat, elf-like to human man, and costumes were not standardized; No one was quite sure what this gift-giver should look like.<\/p>\n\n<figure class=\"caption caption caption\" style=\"float:right\"><img alt=\"Depiction of Santa Claus, Dollar Newspaper, Philadelphia, PA, December 25, 1844\" class=\"media-element file-default\" height=\"282\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Dollar%20Newspaper%20-%20Philadelphia%20PA%20-%2012-25-1844%20%282%29.png\" title=\"Depiction of Santa Claus, Dollar Newspaper, Philadelphia, PA, December 25, 1844\" width=\"300\" \/><figcaption>Early depiction of Santa Claus<br \/>\n\t\tDollar Newspaper (Philadelphia, Pennsylvania)<br \/>\n\t\tDecember 25, 1844<\/figcaption><\/figure><p>It wasn\u2019t until the <a href=\"https:\/\/archive.org\/stream\/gri_33125008808467#page\/n7\/mode\/2up\" rel=\"nofollow\">illustrations of Thomas Nast<\/a>, a German-born New Yorker and <em><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/collections\/articles-databases\/harpweek\">Harper\u2019s Weekly<\/a><\/em> cartoonist, that an enduring image of Santa Claus was established.<\/p>\n\n<p>Creating an entire world for Santa built upon the traditions described by Clement Moore and the influences of <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Belsnickel\" rel=\"nofollow\">German Christmas folklore<\/a>, <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thomas_Nast\" rel=\"nofollow\">Nast<\/a> captured trademark elements of Santa\u2019s image as his drawings evolved. A long white beard, black boots, and red suit trimmed with fur are just a few of these identifying features. Portrayed as a round, cheerful, elderly man, Nast's\u00a0drawings also added some key details to Santa\u2019s backstory: a home at the North Pole and toy-building elf assistants.<\/p>\n\n<p>Santa's celebrity status and iconic appearance was further cemeted in\u00a0roles such as\u00a0Coca Cola\u2019s longstanding <a href=\"http:\/\/www.coca-cola.co.uk\/stories\/history\/advertising\/coca-cola-and-father-christmas-the-sundblom-santa-story\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">advertising campaign<\/a>\u00a0and growing holiday commercialism.\u00a0<\/p>\n\n<p>\u00a0<\/p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n\t<figure class=\"caption caption caption\"><img alt=\"Cover of Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly, December 30, 1871, &amp;quot;Letters from Naughty Children&amp;#039;s Parents&amp;quot;\" class=\"media-element file-default\" height=\"528\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Harper%27s%20weekly%20cover%20-%20dec%2030%201871%20-%20letters%20from%20naughty%20children%27s%20parents.jpg\" title=\"Cover of Harper&amp;#039;s Weekly, December 30, 1871, &amp;quot;Letters from Naughty Children&amp;#039;s Parents&amp;quot;\" width=\"375\" \/><figcaption>\"Letters from Naughty Children's Parents,\" Harper's Weekly, December 30, 1871<\/figcaption><\/figure><\/div>\n\n<p>\u00a0<\/p>\n\n<p><span>A figure rooted in centuries-old legends and decades-long American transformation, Santa Claus as a pop culture icon is here to stay.<\/span>\n\n<\/p><h2>Further Reading<\/h2>\n\n<figure class=\"caption caption caption\" style=\"float:right\"><img alt=\"Santa is an All-American, Chicago Daily Tribune 12-18-1950\" class=\"media-element file-default\" height=\"156\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/Chicago%20Daily%20Tribune%2012-18-1950.png\" title=\"Santa is an All-American, Chicago Daily Tribune 12-18-1950\" width=\"230\" \/><figcaption>Chicago Daily Tribune, December 18, 1950<\/figcaption><\/figure><p>Learn more about the history of Santa Claus\u00a0through the following materials:<\/p>\n\n<ul><li><em><a href=\"http:\/\/catalog.nypl.org\/record=b17783430~S1\">Christmas in America: A History<\/a><\/em><\/li>\n\t<li><em><a href=\"http:\/\/catalog.nypl.org\/record=b14961416~S1\">Encyclopedia of Christmas<\/a><\/em><\/li>\n\t<li><em><a href=\"http:\/\/catalog.nypl.org\/record=b16099065~S1\">Encyclopedia of New York State<\/a><\/em>: \u201cSt. Nicholas\u201d<\/li>\n\t<li><em><a href=\"http:\/\/www.stnicholascenter.org\/pages\/knickerbocker\/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Knickerbocker Santa Claus<\/a><\/em><\/li>\n\t<li><em><a href=\"http:\/\/catalog.nypl.org\/record=b12768319~S1\">Santa Claus, Last of the Wild Men<\/a><\/em><\/li>\n<\/ul><p>Find Thomas Nast\u2019s <em>Harper\u2019s Weekly<\/em> illustrations of Santa Claus in the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/collections\/articles-databases\/harpweek\">HarpWeek<\/a> database. Also search for articles describing early St. Nicholas and\u00a0Santa Claus traditions in the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/collections\/articles-databases\/americas-historical-newspapers\">America\u2019s Historical Newspapers<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nypl.org\/collections\/articles-databases\/proquest-historical-database\">Proquest Historical Newspapers<\/a> databases.<\/p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n\t<figure class=\"caption caption caption\"><img alt=\"First mention of &amp;quot;St. a Claus,&amp;quot; Rivington&amp;#039;s New-New Gazetteer, December 23, 1773\" class=\"media-element file-default\" height=\"63\" src=\"https:\/\/www.nypl.org\/sites\/default\/files\/1st%20mention%20of%20St.%20a%20Claus%20-%20Rivington%27s%20New-York%20Gazetteer.png\" title=\"First mention of &amp;quot;St. a Claus,&amp;quot; Rivington&amp;#039;s New-New Gazetteer, December 23, 1773\" width=\"340\" \/><figcaption>The first mention of a Santa Claus figure:\"St. a Claus,\" Rivington's New-York Gazetteer, December 23, 1773<\/figcaption><\/figure><\/div>\n","safe_summary":"How was the iconic image of Santa born? Several New Yorkers inspired the personality, appearance, and traditions of this holiday favorite."}]},"field_related_divisions":{"und":[{"nid":"5218